Part A: Create and Attach an EBS Volume to EC2
Step 1: Go to EC2 Dashboard → Elastic Block Store → Volumes. Click Create Volume.
Step 2: Choose Volume type (gp3/gp2), set the size, and make sure the Availability Zone matches your EC2 instance's AZ. Click Create Volume.
Step 3: Select the newly created volume → click Actions → Attach Volume.
Step 4: Choose your target EC2 instance from the list. Specify device name (e.g., /dev/xvdf). Click Attach.
Step 5: Connect to your EC2 instance via SSH.
Step 6: Run lsblk to verify the new volume is attached and visible
Part B: Scale EC2 Instance (Change Instance Type)
Step 1: Go to EC2 Dashboard. Select your instance and click Stop (wait for it to stop).
Step 2: Click Actions → Instance Settings → Change Instance Type.
Step 3: Select the new instance type (e.g., from t2.micro to t2.small). Click Apply.
Step 4: Start the instance again. The CPU and RAM are now upgraded.
Part C: Permanently Mount EBS Volume on Linux EC2
Step 1: View current disk status
bash
lsblk
Step 2: Check if disk is already formatted
bash
sudo file -s /dev/xvdbf
Step 3: Format the disk with ext4 filesystem
bash
sudo mkfs.ext4 /dev/xvdbf
Step 4: Create mount directory
bash
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/data
Step 5: Mount the volume
bash
sudo mount /dev/xvdbf /mnt/data
Step 6: Verify mount succeeded
bash
df -h
Step 7: Get disk UUID for permanent mount
bash
sudo blkid /dev/xvdbf
Step 8: Backup existing fstab file
bash
sudo cp /etc/fstab /etc/fstab.backup
Step 9: Open fstab for editing
bash
sudo nano /etc/fstab
Step 10: Add this line at the end of fstab file
text
UUID=ff5b5ce1-ce99-40ff-9869-a52a1a7bec47 /mnt/data ext4 defaults,nofail 0 0
Note: Replace UUID with the one you got from Step 7

Step 11: Save and exit nano
Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

Step 12: Test the fstab entry
bash
sudo mount -a
Step 13: Create a test file
bash
sudo touch /mnt/data/f1
Step 14: Verify file was created
bash
ls -la /mnt/data/
Step 15: Reboot to test persistence
bash
sudo reboot
Step 16: After reboot, verify mount still works
bash
df -h
ls -la /mnt/data/
Part D: Create a Snapshot and Copy to Another Region
Step 1: Go to EC2 → Elastic Block Store → Volumes. Select the volume you want to snapshot.
Step 2: Click Actions → Create Snapshot. Provide a name and description. Click Create Snapshot.
Step 3: Once the snapshot is created, go to EC2 → Snapshots in the source region.
Step 4: Select your snapshot → click Actions → Copy Snapshot.
Step 5: Choose the destination region and click Copy. Switch to the destination region in the console.
Step 6: In the destination region, go to EC2 → Snapshots. Select the copied snapshot → click Actions → Create Volume from Snapshot.
Step 7: Choose the Availability Zone (must match the target EC2 instance). Click Create Volume.
Step 8: Once created, attach the new volume to an EC2 instance in the destination region via Actions → Attach Volume.
